{{globalize/US|date=May 2016}}
'''Lottery games with "lifetime" prizes''', known by names including ''[[Cash4Life]], [[Lucky for Life]],'' and ''Win for Life,'' comprise two types of United States [[lottery]] games in which the top prize is advertised as a lifetime [[Annuity (US financial products)|annuity]]; unlike annuities with a fixed period (such as 25 years), lifetime annuities often pay (sometimes for [[decade|decades]]) until the winner's death.
==Scratch games== Most U.S. lotteries offer at least one [[scratchcard|scratch game]] with lifetime prizes.
These games vary; some lotteries offer multiple price points for "lifetime" games, with the top prize ranging from $50 daily to $1,000,000 yearly. Play for each game varies.
Increasingly, American lotteries have introduced a [[present value|cash option]] for winners of scratch games with such prizes (as they had begun in the 20th century with fixed annuities in almost all games, drawing or scratchcard.)
==Draw games== {{main2|Cash4Life|Lucky for Life}}
The "Win for Life" game (which replaced "[[Lotto South]]") began in 2006 in [[Georgia Lottery|Georgia]], [[Kentucky Lottery|Kentucky]], and [[Virginia Lottery|Virginia]]. Kentucky dropped out in 2011, and Georgia in 2014, leaving Virginia as its only member. "Win for Life" was retired following the September 13, 2014 drawing; it was replaced by $1,000,000 Moneyball.
Players chose six numbers from 1 through 42; seven numbers were drawn, including the "Free Ball". Top prize was $1000-per-week; there was a cash option of $1 million (offered when WFL became a Virginia-only game; when WFL began Virginia offered a $520,000 cash option, but the choice was eliminated the following year as neither Georgia nor Kentucky offered winners a cash option.) Second prize was $52,000 cash.
When Kentucky dropped WFL, Georgia, Kentucky, and Virginia began "[[Decades of Dollars]]", which later added [[Arkansas Lottery|Arkansas]]. On October 19, 2014, Decades of Dollars no longer was available in Arkansas, Georgia, or Kentucky; the three lotteries participated in the launch of "[[Monopoly Millionaires' Club]]", whose sales were suspended in December. Decades of Dollars held its final drawing on April 30, 2015; Virginia then joined the multi-state "[[Cash4Life]]".
In 2015, Kentucky joined Lucky for Life (which began in 2009 as a Connecticut-only game, "Lucky-4-Life") and Virginia joined the rival "Cash4Life". On August 28, 2016, Georgia joined [[Cash4Life]]; both games mentioned here have ''two'' lifetime prize tiers; winners of a "lifetime" prize can choose cash in lieu of annuity payments.
