[[File:Extensive form game 3.1.JPG|300px|right|thumb|Fig. 1: A game beginning with a move by nature]]
In [[game theory]] a '''move by nature''' is a ''decision'' or ''move'' in an [[extensive form game]] made by a player who has no strategic interests in the outcome.  The effect is to add a player, 'Nature', whose practical role is to act as a [[random number generator]].  For instance, if a game of [[Poker]] requires a [[Poker dealer|dealer]] to choose which cards a player is dealt, the dealer plays the role of the '''Nature player'''.

Fig. 1 shows a [[signaling game]] which begins with a move by nature.  Moves by nature are an integral part of games of [[incomplete information]].

